Here is my pre-workout mobility routine that I had posted on my story a couple of weeks ago. A bunch of you guys wanted me to make it a permanent post so that you can refer to it in the future so here you go!
-
I am not a mobility expert by any means. As you can see, I don’t actually know the names of any of these movements. As I got older, I noticed I that I needed to warm up more and more prior to my workouts to feel ready and started incorporating some movements that I found helpful. I’m not trying to be a yoga expert. I’m just trying to loosen myself up to avoid injury and this has certainly helped me with that.
-
Feel free to give some of these a shot as well as others that you find work well for you. Depending on the areas that are tight for you, there may be some other exercises you want to include. Conversely, you may be able to skip some of the ones I do if you don’t find it helpful for you.
-
If you are struggling with 𝐜𝐚𝐥𝐜𝐮𝐥𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐠 your 𝐦𝐚𝐜𝐫𝐨𝐬, setting up 𝐲𝐨𝐮𝐫 𝐝𝐢𝐞𝐭, and designing an 𝐞𝐟𝐟𝐞𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐰𝐨𝐫𝐤𝐨𝐮𝐭 𝐫𝐨𝐮𝐭𝐢𝐧𝐞, check out my 𝐞𝐛𝐨𝐨𝐤 by clicking the 𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐦𝐲 𝐛𝐢𝐨💪🏼.
-
If you’re interested in working with me 1 on 1 for a custom plan tailored to your goals, send me an email for more information on online coaching.

Here is my most recent pull hypertrophy workout that I posted on my story a few days ago as I was doing it. For those of you who didn’t know, I always post my workouts on my story as I do them.
-
This is my second of two pull workouts for the week. The first one is with heavier weight and fewer reps. I posted that one a couple of weeks ago. My second one is with less weight and more reps.

Today’s workout was:

Lat Pulldowns: 4 sets of 10-12
One Arm Machine Rows: 4 sets of 10
Chest Supported Tbar Rows: 3 sets of 12-15
Rear Delt Flyes: 3 sets of 12
Hammer Curls: 3 sets of 20-25

Flat Bench Press: 4 sets of 4 and 1 set of 10

Dips: 3 sets of 10
Dumbbell Lateral Raises: 3 sets of 10

Calves are one of the toughest body parts to develop. Part of the reason is they are fairly dependent on your genetics (to a higher degree than most muscles in my opinion) and they also get trained incorrectly. I'd like to think I have pretty decent calves so I'll share 3 tips on what has helped me the most. Number 3 is the most crucial and is what I will discuss in this video.
-
1. Frequency: Train your calves at least 2-3 times per week with 4-8 sets each workout. You can even do calves at the end of every single workout. Your calves are used to a heavy workload since you've been walking on them your whole life. They can handle the work and you won't be overtraining them.
-
2. Form: Make sure you are actually using your calves when you do calf raises. Slow and controlled on the way down and pause for a second at the top. No bouncing or using momentum. Your calves are a small muscle and it's very easy to cheat and take the emphasis off them by letting your ego get in the way. People care about how much you bench, not how much you calf raise.
-
3. **Huge Drop Sets**: This is the single technique that has helped my calves the most. On your last set of calf raises, choose a weight you can hit for 8-12 reps. Do a drop set and on the drop set count 3 second negatives and pause for a second at the top of each rep. Go to failure and then do another drop set doing the same thing. Do 3 or 4 of these drop sets with the 3 second negatives and 1 second pause at the top with each set to failure. The set should take 2-4 minutes, your calves will be burning, and it will be the sickest pump you've ever gotten. Do this at least twice per week and your calves will grow.

FACE-PULLS by @apfau
-
Face-pulls are by far my favorite rear delt exercise. They are excellent not only for rear delt development but for shoulder health too. However, they're rarely performed correctly.
-
To put the majority of the emphasis on the rear delts, I like to set the pulley at around chest height. From there, focus on pulling straight towards your forehead and externally rotate your shoulders at the top. It should almost look like you're doing a back double bicep at the peak of the contraction. You can do them seated as well.
-
Overall, you need to remember that shoulders are a tiny muscle group and rear delts are just a small part of that tiny muscle group. There's no need to try to load up the weight. Focus on performing the movement correctly and let those rear delts grow 💪🏼.
-

DELOADS by @apfau
-
A deload is a period of time, usually a week, where you back off your volume and/or intensity at the gym. The purpose is to give your body a necessary physical and mental break after a period of intense training to prevent burnout and to ensure you make progress long term.
-
When? I suggest deloading every 6-12 weeks. Closer to 6 weeks if you’re following more of a strength based program and closer to 12 if you focus mostly on hyPERtrophy. If you’re a beginner, you can go longer, probably closer to 6 months. You should do it before you start to feel like you actually need it because at that point, a week might not be enough to recover.
-
How? There is no “wrong” way to deload. Don’t overthink it. The whole point is just to back off and let your body and mind recover. You can reduce your volume by doing less sets or workouts per week, reduce your intensity by doing less weight, a combination of both, or you can even take a complete week off. Personally, I do the same routine with the same sets/reps but I reduce the weight by about 30%.
-
You should deload whether bulking or cutting and can keep your diet the same. You can continue to do cardio but if you do HIIT, you might want to switch to lower intensity for the week. If you decide to drop cardio for the week, then you might want to reduce your calories a little to compensate.

BICEP BLAST by @apfau
-
The bicep has two heads (hence the prefix “bi”). The two heads are the long head and the short head. However, there is an additional muscle, the brachialis, which technically is not part of the bicep but contributes to the overall development of your biceps.
-
The short head is the inner part of the bicep. It can be targeted with preacher curls as well as a generally wider grip. The long head is the outside of the bicep and can be targeted with a narrower grip as well as incline dumbbell curls, cable curls, and barbell curls.
-
The brachialis is a distinct muscle from your bicep. It sits somewhere between the bicep and the tricep. However, it will contribute to overall arm thickness and make your biceps appear larger since it pushes up against your bicep. Hammers curls are a good exercise to hit it.
-

BUDGET BULKING by @apfau
-
Eating to gain muscle can be expensive. As you continue to gain size, your caloric needs will increase which means more food is required and more money spent on groceries. While it’s easy to spend a lot of money on food, there are also plenty of relatively inexpensive options as well.
-
Carbs are usually the least expensive while protein is the most expensive. Potatoes, oats, rice, and bananas are all pretty cheap especially if you buy in bulk (besides the bananas...don’t buy those in bulk). Although there are some expensive brands of chicken breast, it can be found relatively cheaply if you look for deals and buy in bulk. Tuna and eggs are always inexpensive and you can wait for a sale on whey protein that can last for months. For fats, buying peanut butter and nuts in larger quantities is usually the most affordable. If you can handle milk, it’s another inexpensive source of calories. Bulking can be expensive but it doesn’t have to be.

Last week I mentioned that I graduated from law school a few years ago (this photo is from my law school graduation, not Hogwarts). Based on comments I received, I realized most of you didn’t know this. So, why’d I go to law school? Why am I not a lawyer now? How’d I end up doing what I’m doing instead? To answer these questions, let me give you my story.
-
I got into a fitness lifestyle at 15. I knew it was my passion and how I wanted to spend my life. However, I was always led to believe that there was no way to have a career in fitness and I should leave it as a hobby on the side.
-
In college, I wanted to major in exercise science or nutrition but I listened to outside influences and majored in something I had no interest in. Business management. After college, this landed me a job that I did not like.
-
I worked for an insurance company for 2.5 years and hated it so I started thinking about perusing law. Fitness was still my passion but by this point, I had been brainwashed into believing it would never be my way to make a living. Law was always an interest of mine and seemed like a good career path. I quit my job, took the LSAT, got a full scholarship to law school, and I graduated with my J.D. in 2018.
-
Although I always was and still am interested in law, I was never too interested in actually being a lawyer. In law school, I began to realize this more and more and decided it was time to stop listening to everyone else and do what I wanted.  I saw people using social media to build online fitness businesses and thought "why not me?" My true passion is helping people reach their fitness goals and I was determined to make fitness my career path. I began taking Instagram seriously. I didn’t miss a day posting in over three years and with a lot of time, effort, and consistency, began to grow my following and my online coaching business as well.
-
I don't have many fears in life but regret is one thing that scares me. I knew I would be sitting at a desk for the rest of my life thinking "what if?" If my business ever failed I would at least be able to say I tried. However, things have gone significantly better than I ever could have imagined.

node.text:
GET BACK TO THE GYM by @apfau
-
Whether you’ve been training at home for a while or have just taken an extended break from working out all together, once you’re ready to go back to the gym, it’s important to approach it intelligently.
-
It’s very easy to feel the need to make up for lost time and try to get back any lost gains as soon as possible. However, that approach will probably make the process of regaining muscle take longer.
-
First, you likely lost strength. Don’t be discouraged and don’t try to ignore it by attempting to lift the same weights as before. The last thing you want is to hurt yourself and be out of the gym again after this long break. Lower the weight and work your way back up.
-
Second, you’re going to get sore no matter what you do. You’re going to get significantly more sore if you’re pushing every set to or very close to failure. Try to stop several reps short of failure for the first couple of weeks. Otherwise, you probably won’t be able to move for several days and be forced to take extra days off to recover.
-
Lastly, look at this as a fresh start and have a plan. Don’t just go into the gym and wing it. Hopefully you spent part of these past few months learning about how you should be training to reach your goals. Now it’s just time to implement it.
-
You’re going to get your gains back. Regaining lost muscle is a lot quicker than gaining muscle the first time. Have a plan and don’t go from 0-100 too quickly or else you’ll actually be slowing down the process and risking injury instead.

LAT PULLDOWNS by @apfau
-
Did you know that a wider grip on pull-ups and pull downs actually works less of your lats than going narrower? Using a slightly outside shoulder width grip will increase your range of motion, engage your lats more, and allow you to use more weight. All of these will yield better lat growth. A wide grip for wide lats is simply not correct.
-
Going wider, as long as it’s not too wide to the point where your shoulders are put in a compromised position, isn’t necessarily “wrong” but it actually targets more of the teres major, which is a smaller muscle above the lats. If that’s what you’re going for, that’s fine. However, most people going wide are doing so with the thought that it’s the way to go for maximum lat involvement.
-
Another common error people make when doing lat pulldowns is leaning too far back and using momentum. The opposite of that is also common where people sit too upright while failing to lean back at all. Instead, you want to lean back slightly, retract your scapula, stick your chest up, and pull to around your upper chest while making sure you are pulling with your elbows.

ZUCCHINI NOODLES VS. PASTA by @apfau
-
Neither of these are “better” than the other. They are both perfectly fine to eat depending on your goals. The regular spaghetti has over 40 carbs per serving whereas the zucchini noodles have less than 2 (that’s right...2) carbs for an equal amount. If you’re looking to save calories without reducing the volume of food you’re eating, zucchini noodles are an excellent substitute. If you need the carbs and saving calories is not a concern, then regular pasta might be a better choice for you.
-
If you’re dieting and find yourself struggling with hunger, low calorie/high volume substitutes like these are helpful. Cauliflower substitutes are another game changer. That doesn’t mean you can’t also eat regular pasta when cutting but selecting higher volume foods when in a caloric deficit is the best way to deal with hunger since you’re still eating the same volume of food but with substantially less calories. Swipe left for a couple of posts from @collegenutritionist showing additional “regular” pasta nutrition comparisons and veggie pasta comparisons.

node.text:
WHEY PROTEIN
-
As I’ve said many times before, there is nothing magical about protein supplements. If you can get enough protein through food alone then you certainly do not need them. Most people do find it challenging to get enough protein through food alone which is why protein supplements are useful. A lot of people complain that they have experienced digestion and skin issues with whey in the past. It’s important to realize that not all whey protein supplements are equal.
-
Just like you wouldn’t expect a $1 steak from the dollar store to be as good as a more expensive cut of steak from Whole Foods, you shouldn’t expect a cheap whey protein to be as high of quality as a more trustworthy brand. If you experience digestion and skin issues, chances are it’s due to the lactose. Cheaper whey proteins use whey concentrate which isn’t “bad” but does contain lactose which causes issues for some people. It’s also common for cheaper whey proteins to contain fillers which can also cause issues. @legion Whey+ uses whey isolate instead of concentrate. More specifically, Whey+ is 100% natural grass-fed whey isolate made with milk from small, sustainable dairy farms in Ireland. Whey isolate removes the lactose. Whey+ does not have any artificial fillers, added sugars, and is 100% natural.
-
Further, it’s not uncommon for the protein content on the label to be inaccurate. There are certain tactics that exist within the supplement industry which essentially allows companies to list a higher amount of protein on the label than what is actually included per serving. For that reason, I always suggest doing your research before purchasing any supplements. My eyes were originally opened to this because I was fooled myself when I was using a whey protein which claimed to have 25 grams per serving which I later found out only had 3-5 😢. You can look up @legion Whey+ on Lab Door where it was found to contain the full amount of protein that the label promises.
-
